{
  "text": "In search for a more efficient and less difficult instrumentation, investigators have proposed lasers as alternatives or adjuncts for SRP in periodontal therapy [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The thermomechanical ablation mechanism and the high absorption of its wavelength by water may qualify the Er:YAG laser in particular as an effective tool in periodontal and also in general dental applications . The effects of Er:YAG laser irradiation on periodontally involved root surfaces have been examined and its capacity to remove subgingival calculus and superficial layers of infected cementum has been demonstrated in vitro [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ). In comparison with other laser systems, the Er:YAG laser led to minor structural alterations on the root surface with no side-effects on the dental pulp [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . The Er:YAG laser showed a high bactericidal potential and the capacity to reduce lipopolysaccharide contamination of the root surface [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . The clinical outcome 6 months after periodontal therapy with an Er:YAG laser was equivalent to SRP (Schwarz et al. 2001a, b) .",
